Definition 2 Let $\mathcal{M}$ (resp. $\mathcal{E}$) be the class of $\Omega$-homomorphisms with injective (resp. surjective) underlying maps. A variety of $\Omega$-algebras is a full subcategory of $\textup{\bf Alg}(\Omega)$, which is closed under the formation of products, $\mathcal{M}$-subobjects (subalgebras) and $\mathcal{E}$-quotients (homomorphic images). The objects (resp. morphisms) of a variety are called algebras (resp. homomorphisms).
Definition 16 Given a powerset theory $\textup{\bf X}\xrightarrow{P}\textup{\bf A}_{it}$ and a reduct B of A, a bornological theory in X induced by the pair $(P,\textup{\bf B})$ is the functor $\textup{\bf X}\xrightarrow{T}\textup{\bf B}_{it}$, which is defined as the composition $\textup{\bf X}\xrightarrow{P}\textup{\bf A}_{it}\xrightarrow{\|-\|_{it}}% \textup{\bf B}_{it}$.
Definition 5 Let A be a variety of algebras, the elements of which have a 0-ary operation $\bot$. 1. A term $p(\vec{x},\vec{y})$ is an (A-)ideal term in $\vec{y}$ if $p(\vec{x},\vec{\bot})=\bot$ is an identity in A. 2. A non-empty subset $\mathcal{I}$ of an A-algebra $A$ is called an (A-)ideal provided that for every ideal term $p(\vec{x},\vec{y})$ in $\vec{y}$, $\vec{a}\in A^{n}$, $\vec{i}\in\mathcal{I}^{m}$, it follows that $p(\vec{a},\vec{i})\in\mathcal{I}$.
Definition 13 A bornological space is a pair $(X,\mathcal{B})$, where $X$ is a set and $\mathcal{B}$ (a bornology on $X$) is a subfamily of $\mathcal{P}X$ (the elements of which are called bounded sets), which satisfies the following axioms: 1. $X=\bigcup\mathcal{B}$ $(=\bigcup_{B\in\mathcal{B}}B)$; 2. if $B\in\mathcal{B}$ and $D\subseteq B$, then $D\in\mathcal{B}$; 3. if $\mathcal{S}\subseteq\mathcal{B}$ is finite, then $\bigcup\mathcal{S}\in\mathcal{B}$. Given bornological spaces $(X_{1},\mathcal{B}_{1})$ and $(X_{2},\mathcal{B}_{2})$, a map $X_{1}\xrightarrow{f}X_{2}$ is called bounded provided that $\mathcal{P}f(B_{1})\in\mathcal{B}_{2}$ for every $B_{1}\in\mathcal{B}_{1}$. Born is the construct of bornological spaces and bounded maps.
Definition 3 Given a variety A, a reduct of A is a pair $(\|-\|,\textup{\bf B})$, where B is a variety such that $\Omega_{\textup{\bf B}}\subseteq\Omega_{\textup{\bf A}}$ (every primitive operation of B is a primitive operation of A), and $\textup{\bf A}\xrightarrow{\|-\|}\textup{\bf B}$ is a concrete functor. The pair $(\textup{\bf A},\|-\|)$ is called then an extension of B.
Definition 8 Given a variety of algebras A with a 0-ary operation, $\textup{\bf A}_{it}$ is the construct, whose objects are A-ideals, and whose morphisms are maps $\mathcal{I}_{1}\xrightarrow{\varphi}\mathcal{I}_{2}$, which preserve the ideal terms as follows: 1. for every ideal term $p(\vec{y})$ in $\vec{y}$, $\varphi(p(\vec{i}))=p(\varphi(\vec{i}))$ for every $\vec{i}\in\mathcal{I}_{1}^{n}$; 2. for every ideal term $p(\vec{x},\vec{y})$ in $\vec{y}$, there exist an ideal term $t(\vec{x}\cup\vec{z},\vec{y})$ in $\vec{y}$ (in which the notation ’’$\vec{x}\cup\vec{z}$” means that one adds more variables to $\vec{x}$, e.g., taking $x_{1},x_{2},z_{1},z_{2}$ instead of $x_{1},x_{2}$, but not to $\vec{y}$), and a family of ideal terms $\overrightarrow{s_{u}(\vec{v_{u}},\vec{w_{u}})}_{u\in\vec{z}}$ in $\vec{w_{u}}$ such that $\varphi(p(\vec{a},\vec{i}))=t(\varphi(\vec{a})\cup\varphi(\overrightarrow{s_{u% }(\vec{{a}^{\prime}_{u}},\vec{{i}^{\prime}_{u}})}_{u\in\vec{z}}),\varphi(\vec{% i}))$ for every $\vec{a}\in\mathcal{I}_{1}^{n}$, $\vec{i}\in\mathcal{I}_{1}^{m}$, where $\vec{{a}^{\prime}_{u}}\subseteq\vec{a}$, $\vec{{i}^{\prime}_{u}}\subseteq\vec{i}$.
Definition 17 Let $T$ be a bornological theory in a category X. $\textup{\bf Born}(T)$ is the concrete category over X, whose objects ($T$-bornological spaces or $T$-spaces) are pairs $(X,\tau)$, where $X$ is an X-object and $\tau$ ($T$-bornology on $X$) is an ideal of $TX$ such that $\top\in\langle{\tau}\rangle_{\textup{\bf A}}$, and whose morphisms ($T$-bounded X-morphisms) $(X_{1},\tau_{1})\xrightarrow{f}(X_{2},\tau_{2})$ are X-morphisms $X_{1}\xrightarrow{f}X_{2}$ such that $Tf(\alpha)\in\tau_{2}$ for every $\alpha\in\tau_{1}$ ($T$-boundedness).
Definition 11 Let A be a subcategory of B, and let $B$ be a B-object. 1. An A-reflection (or A-reflection arrow) for $B$ is a B-morphism $B\xrightarrow{r}A$ from $B$ to an A-object $A$ with the following universal property: for every B-morphism $B\xrightarrow{f}{A}^{\prime}$ from $B$ into some A-object ${A}^{\prime}$, there exists a unique A-morphism $A\xrightarrow{{f}^{\prime}}{A}^{\prime}$ such that the triangle $\xymatrix{B\ar[r]^{-}{r}\ar[rd]_{-}{f}&A\ar@{.>}[d]^{-}{{f}^{\prime}}\\ &{A}^{\prime}}$ commutes. 2. A is called a reflective subcategory of B provided that each B-object has an A-reflection.
Definition 23 Given a bornological theory $\textup{\bf X}\xrightarrow{T}\textup{\bf B}_{it}$, $\textup{\bf BornSys}(T)$ is the comma category ${(1_{\textup{\bf B}_{it}}\downarrow T)}$, concrete over the product category $\textup{\bf X}\times\textup{\bf B}_{it}$, whose objects ($T$-bornological systems or $T$-systems) are triples $(X,\kappa,B)$, which are made by $\textup{\bf B}_{it}$-morphisms $B\xrightarrow{\kappa}TX$ such that $\top\in\langle{\mathcal{P}\kappa(B)}\rangle_{\textup{\bf A}}$, and whose morphisms ($T$-bounded morphisms) $(X_{1},\kappa_{1},B_{1})\xrightarrow{(f,\varphi)}(X_{2},\kappa_{2},B_{2})$ are $\textup{\bf X}\times\textup{\bf B}_{it}$-morphisms $(X_{1},B_{1})\xrightarrow{(f,\varphi)}(X_{2},B_{2})$, making the diagram $\xymatrix{B_{1}\ar[d]_{\kappa_{1}}\ar[rr]^{\varphi}&&B_{2}\ar[d]^{\kappa_{2}}% \\ TX_{1}\ar[rr]_{Tf}&&TX_{2}}$ commute.
Definition 1 Let $\Omega=(n_{\lambda})_{\lambda\in\Lambda}$ be a (possibly proper or empty) class of cardinal numbers. An $\Omega$-algebra is a pair $(A,(\omega^{A}_{\lambda})_{\lambda\in\Lambda})$, which comprises a set $A$ and a family of maps $A^{n_{\lambda}}\xrightarrow{\omega^{A}_{\lambda}}A$ ($n_{\lambda}$-ary primitive operations on $A$). An $\Omega$-homomorphism $(A,(\omega^{A}_{\lambda})_{\lambda\in\Lambda})\xrightarrow{\varphi}(B,(\omega^% {B}_{\lambda})_{\lambda\in\Lambda})$ is a map $A\xrightarrow{\varphi}B$, which makes the diagram $\xymatrix@1{A^{n_{\lambda}}\ar[d]_{-}{\omega^{A}_{\lambda}}\ar[rr]^{-}{\varphi% ^{n_{\lambda}}}&&B^{n_{\lambda}}\ar[d]^{-}{\omega^{B}_{\lambda}}\\ A\ar[rr]_{-}{\varphi}&&B\\ }$ commute for every $\lambda\in\Lambda$. $\textup{\bf Alg}(\Omega)$ is the construct of $\Omega$-algebras and $\Omega$-homomorphisms.
Definition 19 A complete lattice $L$ is called ideally completely distributive at $\top_{L}$ provided that for every non-empty family $\{S_{i}\,|\,i\in I\}$ of lattice ideals of $L$, $\bigwedge_{i\in I}(\bigvee S_{i})=\top_{L}$ implies $\bigvee_{h\in H}(\bigwedge_{i\in I}h(i))=\top_{L}$, where $H$ is the set of all choice maps on $\bigcup_{i\in I}S_{i}$, i.e., maps $I\xrightarrow{h}\bigcup_{i\in I}S_{i}$ such that $h(i)\in S_{i}$ for every $i\in I$.
Definition 6 Given a $\textup{\bf Lat}_{\bot}$-object $L$ with the smallest element $\bot_{L}$, a subset $\mathcal{I}\subseteq L$ is said to be an ideal of $L$ provided that the following conditions are fulfilled: 1. for every finite subset $S\subseteq L$, $\bigvee S\in\mathcal{I}$; 2. for every $a\in L$ and every $i\in I$, $a\wedge i\in\mathcal{I}$.
Definition 14 A powerset theory in a category X (ground category of the theory) is a functor $\textup{\bf X}\xrightarrow{P}\textup{\bf A}_{it}$ to the category of ideals of a variety A, with the additional property that $PX$ lies in A for every $X\in\textup{\bf X}$.
Definition 4.1. A cyclic operad $P$ is positive if $P(\,\,)$ is terminal in $\mathcal{V}$. We write $\mathbf{Cyc}^{\uparrow}$ for the full subcategory of $\mathbf{Cyc}$ consisting of the positive cyclic operads.
Definition 2.4. A (colored) collection in $\mathcal{V}$ consists of the following: • An involutive set $\mathfrak{C}=\operatorname{Col}(P)$, where we typically write the the involution as $c\mapsto c^{\dagger}$. • A set of objects $P(c_{0},c_{1},\dots,c_{n})\in\mathcal{V}$, one for each (possibly empty) profile in $\mathfrak{C}$. • If $\sigma\in\Sigma_{n}^{+}$, maps $\sigma^{*}:P(\underline{c})=P(c_{0},c_{1},\dots,c_{n})\to P(c_{\sigma(0)},% \dots,c_{\sigma(n)})=P(\underline{c}\sigma)$ satisfying $(\sigma^{\prime})^{*}\sigma^{*}=(\sigma\sigma^{\prime})^{*}$ and $(\operatorname{id})^{*}=\operatorname{id}$. A morphism $P\to Q$ between two collections consists of: • an involutive function $f:\operatorname{Col}(P)\to\operatorname{Col}(Q)$, and • for each profile $\underline{c}$ in $\operatorname{Col}(P)$, a morphism $f_{\underline{c}}:P(\underline{c})=P(c_{0},c_{1},\dots,c_{n})\to Q(fc_{0},fc_{% 1},\dots,fc_{n})=Q(f\underline{c})$ in $\mathcal{V}$, so that for each profile $\underline{c}$ the diagram $\tikzcd P(\underline{c})\rar{\sigma^{*}}\dar[swap]{f_{\underline{c}}}&P(% \underline{c}\sigma)\dar{f_{\underline{c}\sigma}}\\ Q(f\underline{c})\rar[swap]{\sigma^{*}}&Q(f\underline{c}\sigma)$ commutes.
Definition 2.6. A cyclic operad $P$ in $\mathcal{V}$ consists of a collection (also called $P$) as well as • distinguished elements $\operatorname{id}_{c}:\mathbf{1}_{\mathcal{V}}\to P(c^{\dagger},c)$ for each $c\in\mathfrak{C}$, and • if $\underline{c}=c_{0},\dots,c_{n}$, $\underline{d}=d_{0},\dots,d_{m}$, $0\leq i\leq n$, $0\leq j\leq m$, and $c_{i}=d_{j}^{\dagger}$, a map $\circ_{i}^{j}:P(\underline{c})\otimes P(\underline{d})\to P(\underline{c}\circ% _{i}^{j}\underline{d}).$ These data should satisfy a short list of axioms: C.1) If $\|x\|=n$ and $\|y\|=m$, we have $(\tau^{m-j+i})^{*}(x\circ_{i}^{j}y)=y\circ_{j}^{i}x$. C.2) If in addition $\|z\|=p$, $0\leq k\leq p$, and $k\neq j$, we have $(x\circ_{i}^{j}y)\circ_{\beta_{j,i}^{m,n}(k)}^{\ell}z=x\circ_{i}^{\alpha_{k,p}% ^{m}(j)}(y\circ_{k}^{\ell}z),$ whenever the indicated compositions are defined. C.3) Suppose that $\sigma_{1}\in\Sigma_{n}^{+}$, $\sigma_{2}\in\Sigma_{m}^{+}$, and $\sigma=(\alpha_{\sigma_{1}(i),m}\amalg\beta_{\sigma_{2}(j),\sigma_{1}(i)})(% \sigma_{1}\amalg\sigma_{2})(\alpha_{i,m}\amalg\beta_{j,i})^{-1},$ that is, $\sigma$ is defined so that the diagram $\tikzcd[columnsep=3cm]{[0,n]\setminus\{i\}}\amalg{[0,m]\setminus\{j\}}\dar[% swap]{\sigma_{1}\amalg\sigma_{2}}\rar{\alpha_{i,m}\amalg\beta_{j,i}}&{[0,n+m-1% ]}\dar{\sigma}\\ {[0,n]\setminus\{\sigma_{1}(i)\}}\amalg{[0,m]\setminus\{\sigma_{2}(j)\}}\rar[% swap]{\alpha_{\sigma_{1}(i),m}\amalg\beta_{\sigma_{2}(j),\sigma_{1}(i)}}&{[0,n% +m-1]}$ commutes. Then $(\sigma_{1}^{*}x)\circ_{i}^{j}(\sigma_{2}^{*}y)=\sigma^{*}(x\circ_{\sigma_{1}(% i)}^{\sigma_{2}(j)}y)$. C.4) $x\circ_{i}^{1}\operatorname{id}_{c}=x$ whenever this is defined, and $\tau^{*}\operatorname{id}_{c}=\operatorname{id}_{c^{\dagger}}$. Morphisms of cyclic operads are precisely the morphisms of the underlying collections which are compatible with the $\operatorname{id}_{c}$ and the $\circ_{i}^{j}$. We denote the resulting category by $\mathbf{Cyc}(\mathcal{V})$. We write $\mathbf{Cyc}_{\mathfrak{C}}(\mathcal{V})$ for the subcategory consisting of those maps with $\operatorname{Col}(P)=\operatorname{Col}(Q)=\mathfrak{C}$, and $f=\operatorname{id}_{\mathfrak{C}}$. Often we will omit the ground category $\mathcal{V}$ from the notation, and write $\mathbf{Cyc}$ instead of $\mathbf{Cyc}(\mathcal{V})$.
Definition 2.10. A non-unital Markl cyclic operad $P$ in $\mathcal{V}$ consists of a collection (also called $P$) equipped with $\circ_{i}^{j}$ operations as in Definition 2.6 satisfying axioms (C.1), (C.2), and (C.3).
Definition 4.7. A non-$\Sigma$ collection is defined similarly to a collection (Definition 2.4), except that $\sigma^{*}$ is only defined for $\sigma$ in the subgroup $\langle\tau_{n+1}\rangle\leq\Sigma_{n}^{+}$. Likewise, a non-$\Sigma$ cyclic operad is defined similarly to a cyclic operad (Definition 2.6) except that it only has an underlying non-$\Sigma$ collection and, furthermore, (C.3) is replaced with (C.$3^{\text{non-}\Sigma}$).
Definition 3.2 (The forgetful functor). Suppose that $P\in\mathbf{Cyc}$. We define an object $FP\in\mathbf{Opd}$ as follows. First, define $\operatorname{Col}(FP)\coloneqq\operatorname{Col}(P)$ and $FP(c_{1},\dots,c_{n};c_{0})\coloneqq P(c_{0}^{\dagger},c_{1},\dots,c_{n}).$ Now, given biprofiles $(c_{1},\dots,c_{n};c_{0})$ and $(d_{1},\dots,d_{m};d_{0})$ with $d_{0}=c_{i}$, we have $\tikzcd FP(\underline{c};c_{0})\otimes FP(\underline{d};d_{0})\rar{=}\dar[swap% ,dashed,"\circ_{i}",color=violet]&P(c_{0}^{\dagger},\underline{c})\otimes P(d_% {0}^{\dagger},\underline{d})\dar{\circ_{i}^{0}}\\ FP(\underline{c}\circ_{i}\underline{d};c_{0})\rar[swap]{=}&P(c_{0}^{\dagger},% \underline{c}\circ_{i}\underline{d})=P((c_{0}^{\dagger},\underline{c})\circ_{i% }^{0}(d_{0}^{\dagger},\underline{d}))$ The symmetric group actions and the identities are induced from those of $P$.
Definition 6.1. Suppose that $f:P\to Q$ is a map in $\mathbf{Cyc}(\mathbf{sSet})$ or $\mathbf{Opd}(\mathbf{sSet})$. We say that $f$ is a Dwyer–Kan equivalence (resp. isofibration) if • $f$ is locally a weak equivalence (resp. Kan fibration) of simplicial sets, and • the functor $[f]:[P]\to[Q]$ is an equivalence of categories (resp. isofibration of categories). If $f:P\to Q$ is a map in $\mathbf{Cyc}(\mathbf{sSet})$, we say that $f$ is a positive Dwyer–Kan equivalence (resp. positive isofibration) if $G(f):G(P)\to G(Q)$ is a Dwyer–Kan equivalence (resp. an isofibration).
6.2 Definition. Let $\mathcal{F}$ be a symmetric bispectrum. Let $\mathcal{F}[n]$ be the usual $n$th shift of $\mathcal{F}$ in the $\mathbb{G}_{m}^{\wedge 1}$-direction. For each $i\geqslant 0$ let $\mathcal{F}(i)$ and $\mathcal{F}[1](i)$ be the $i$th weights of $\mathcal{F}$ and $\mathcal{F}[1]$ respectively (see Notation 2.3). Recall that there is a map of symmetric bispectra $\upsilon_{\mathcal{F}}:\mathbb{G}_{m}^{\wedge 1}\wedge\mathcal{F}\to\mathcal{F% }[1]$ defined as follows: for each weight $i\geqslant 0$ it is the composition of maps of $S^{1}$-spectra $\mathbb{G}_{m}^{\wedge 1}\wedge\mathcal{F}(i)\xrightarrow{tw}\mathcal{F}(i)% \wedge\mathbb{G}_{m}^{\wedge 1}\xrightarrow{u}\mathcal{F}(i+1)\xrightarrow{% \chi_{i,1}}\mathcal{F}(1+i)=\mathcal{F}[1](i),$ where $\chi_{i,1}$ is the shuffle permutation. Sometimes we write $\upsilon$ to denote $\upsilon_{\mathcal{F}}$ dropping $\mathcal{F}$ from notation. Notice that $\upsilon_{\mathcal{F}}$ cannot be defined for nonsymmetric bispectra.
2.1 Definition. We define $SH_{\operatorname{nis}}^{fr}(k)$ as a full subcategory in $SH_{\operatorname{nis}}(k)$ consisting of those bispectra $\mathcal{E}$ satisfying the following conditions: (1) each motivic space $\mathcal{E}_{i,j}$ of $\mathcal{E}$ is a space with framed correspondences, i.e. a pointed simplicial sheaf defined on the category of framed correspondences $Fr_{*}(k)$; (2) the structure maps $\mathcal{E}_{i,j}\to\underline{\operatorname{Hom}}(S^{1},\mathcal{E}_{i+1,j})$, $\mathcal{E}_{i,j}\to\underline{\operatorname{Hom}}(\mathbb{G}_{m}^{\wedge 1},% \mathcal{E}_{i,j+1})$ preserve framed correspondences; (3) for every $j\geqslant 0$ the framed presheaves of stable homotopy groups $\pi_{*}(\mathcal{E}_{*,j})$ of the $S^{1}$-spectrum $\mathcal{E}_{*,j}$ are stable, radditive and $\mathbb{A}^{1}$-invariant; (4) (Cancellation Theorem) for every $j\geqslant 0$ the structure map $\mathcal{E}_{*,j}\to\underline{\operatorname{Hom}}(\mathbb{G}_{m}^{\wedge 1},% \mathcal{E}_{*,j+1})$ of $S^{1}$-spectra is a stable local equivalence.
5.3 Definition. (1) We denote by $\mathcal{F}r_{0}(k)$ the category enriched over $Shv_{\bullet}(Sm/k)$ whose objects are those of $Sm/k$ and $Shv_{\bullet}(Sm/k)$-objects given by $Fr_{0}(U\times-,V)$, $U,V\in Sm/k$. It is indeed a $Shv_{\bullet}(Sm/k)$-category by Lemma 5.1. Note that $\mathcal{F}r_{0}(k)$ is $Shv_{\bullet}(Sm/k)$-symmetric monoidal with $U\otimes V:=U\times V$. Clearly, its underlying category is $Fr_{0}(k)$, i.e. the category of smooth $k$-schemes and framed correspondences of level 0. (2) Denote by $\mathrm{Fun}(\mathcal{F}r_{0}(k)):=[\mathcal{F}r_{0}(k),Shv_{\bullet}(Sm/k)]$ the $Shv_{\bullet}(Sm/k)$-category of enriched functors from $\mathcal{F}r_{0}(k)$ to $Shv_{\bullet}(Sm/k)$. It is closed symmetric monoidal by Day’s Theorem [4]. Its monoidal unit $[pt,-]$ is represented by $pt\in\mathcal{F}r_{0}(k)$. By [5, 2.4] $\mathrm{Fun}(\mathcal{F}r_{0}(k))$ is tensored and cotensored over $Shv_{\bullet}(Sm/k)$. (3) We can consider the category $\Delta^{{\textrm{\rm op}}}\mathrm{Fun}(\mathcal{F}r_{0}(k))$ of simplicial objects in $\mathrm{Fun}(\mathcal{F}r_{0}(k))$. By [5, 2.4] $\Delta^{{\textrm{\rm op}}}\mathrm{Fun}(\mathcal{F}r_{0}(k))$ is tensored and cotensored over pointed motivic spaces $\mathbb{M}_{\bullet}:=\Delta^{{\textrm{\rm op}}}Shv_{\bullet}(Sm/k)$. Denote by $Sp_{S^{1}}[\mathcal{F}r_{0}(k)]$ the category of $S^{1}$-spectra associated with the category $\Delta^{{\textrm{\rm op}}}\mathrm{Fun}(\mathcal{F}r_{0}(k))$ and call it the category of spectral functors. By definition, the underlying $S^{1}$-spectrum of a spectral functor $\mathcal{X}\in Sp_{S^{1}}[\mathcal{F}r_{0}(k)]$ is its evaluation $\mathcal{X}(pt)$ at $pt$.
7.1 Definition. (1) We say that a framed spectral functor $\mathcal{X}\in SH_{S^{1}}^{fr}[\mathcal{F}r_{0}(k)]$ is effective if for all $n>0$, $U\in Sm/k$ and finitely generated field $K/k$ the ordinary $S^{1}$-spectrum $\mathcal{X}(\mathbb{G}_{m}^{\wedge n}\times U)(\widehat{\Delta}^{\bullet}_{K})$ is stably trivial. In other words, $\mathcal{X}\in SH_{S^{1}}^{fr}[\mathcal{F}r_{0}(k)]$ is effective if and only if its evaluation bispectrum $ev_{\mathbb{G}_{m}}(\mathcal{X}(-\times U))=(\mathcal{X}(U),\mathcal{X}(% \mathbb{G}_{m}^{\wedge 1}\times U),\ldots)$ is effective in the sense of Definition 3.5. (2) The full subcategory of $SH_{S^{1}}^{fr}[\mathcal{F}r_{0}(k)]$ consisting of the effectrive spectral functors is called the category of framed motives and denoted by ${\mathcal{SH}}^{fr}(k)$.
6.1 Definition. (1) A spectral functor $\mathcal{X}\in Sp_{S^{1}}[\mathcal{F}r_{0}(k)]$ is called a framed spectral functor if $\diamond$ for every $U\in Sm/k$ the bispectrum (3) $ev_{\mathbb{G}_{m}}(\mathcal{X}(-\times U))=(\mathcal{X}(U),\mathcal{X}(% \mathbb{G}_{m}^{\wedge 1}\times U),\mathcal{X}(\mathbb{G}_{m}^{\wedge 2}\times U% ),\ldots)$ is a framed bispectrum in the sense of Definition 2.1, i.e. $ev_{\mathbb{G}_{m}}(\mathcal{X}(-\times U))\in SH_{\operatorname{nis}}^{fr}(k)$; $\diamond$ for every $U\in Sm/k$ the canonical map $pr:\mathcal{X}(\mathbb{A}^{1}\times U)\to\mathcal{X}(U)$ is a stable local equivalence of $S^{1}$-spectra; $\diamond$ it is Nisnevich excisive in the sense that for every elementary Nisnevich square in $Sm/k$ $\xymatrix{U^{\prime}\ar[r]\ar[d]&Y^{\prime}\ar[d]\\ U\ar[r]&Y}$ the square of the $S^{1}$-spectra $\xymatrix{\mathcal{X}(U^{\prime})\ar[r]\ar[d]&\mathcal{X}(Y^{\prime})\ar[d]\\ \mathcal{X}(U)\ar[r]&\mathcal{X}(Y)}$ is locally homotopy cartesian (=homotopy cocartesian in the stable structure). (2) We define a category $SH_{S^{1}}^{fr}[\mathcal{F}r_{0}(k)]$ as follows. Its objects are the framed spectral functors and morphisms are defined as $SH_{S^{1}}^{fr}[\mathcal{F}r_{0}(k)](\mathcal{X},\mathcal{Y}):=SH_{% \operatorname{nis}}^{fr}(k)(ev_{\mathbb{G}_{m}}(\mathcal{X}),ev_{\mathbb{G}_{m% }}(\mathcal{Y})).$ We call $SH_{S^{1}}^{fr}[\mathcal{F}r_{0}(k)]$ the category of framed spectral functors.
3.5 Definition. Let $\mathcal{E}=(\mathcal{E}(0),\mathcal{E}(1),\ldots)\in SH_{\operatorname{nis}}^% {fr}(k)$ be a framed bispectrum in the sense of Definition 2.1. We say that $\mathcal{E}$ is effective if the total spectrum $\mathcal{E}(j)(\widehat{\Delta}^{\bullet}_{K})$ is stably trivial, i.e. equals zero in $SH$, for all positive weights $j>0$ and all finitely generated fields $K/k$. The full subcategory of $SH_{\operatorname{nis}}^{fr}(k)$ of effective framed bispectra will be denoted by $SH_{\operatorname{nis}}^{fr,\,eff}(k)$.
6.5 Definition. Set $\mathcal{M}_{fr}^{E}:=\operatorname{colim}(\mathbb{G}C_{*}Fr^{E}[0]\to\mathbb{% G}C_{*}Fr^{E}[1]\to\cdots)$. By construction, $ev_{\mathbb{G}_{m}}(\mathcal{M}_{fr}^{E})=\operatorname{colim}_{n}ev_{\mathbb{% G}_{m}}(\mathbb{G}C_{*}Fr^{E}[n])$. Each $\mathbb{G}C_{*}Fr^{E}[n]$ is a framed spectral functor, hence so is $\mathcal{M}_{fr}^{E}$.
Definition 2.2. Let us recall the precise definition introduced by Beck [6]. Assume that $T_{1}=(T_{1},\mu_{1},\eta_{1})$ and $T_{2}=(T_{2},\mu_{2},\eta_{2})$ are monads (formerly called triples) on a category ${\tt C}$. A distributive law guarantees that for every $T_{2}$-algebra $A$ in ${\tt C}$, the object $T_{2}(A)\in{\tt C}$ has the structure of a $T_{1}$-algebra in a very explicit way. More precisely, a distributive law is a natural transformation $\lambda:T_{1}T_{2}\to T_{2}T_{1},$ such that, for every $T_{2}$-algebra $A=(A,\alpha\colon T_{2}(A)\to A)$, the object $T_{2}(A)\in{\tt C}$ is a $T_{1}$-algebra with structure morphism $T_{1}T_{2}A\xrightarrow{\;\lambda\;}T_{2}T_{1}A\xrightarrow{\;T_{2}\alpha\;}T_% {2}A.$ This imposes certain conditions on $\lambda$ whose explicit form can be found in [6]; see also [14, §3]. In this situation, the endofunctor $T=T_{2}T_{1}$ is again a monad, with structure transformations $\mu=T_{2}\mu_{1}\circ\mu_{2}T_{1}^{2}\circ T_{2}\lambda T_{1},\qquad\eta=\eta_% {1}\circ\eta_{2}\circ T_{1}.$ The equality $T(X)=T_{2}\big{(}T_{1}(X)\big{)},\qquad X\in{\tt C},$ may be interpreted as saying that the free $T$-algebra on $X$ is (as an object of ${\tt C}$) naturally isomorphic to the free $T_{2}$-algebra generated by the free $T_{1}$-algebra on $X$.
Definition 2.5. We say that the map ${\mathcal{D}}$ of equation (3) is an (operadic homogeneous quadratic) distributive law of ${\mathcal{P}}_{1}$ over ${\mathcal{P}}_{2}$ if the map $\xi(n)$ is an isomorphism for every $n\geq 2$. We express this fact by writing ${\mathcal{D}}\colon{\mathcal{P}}_{1}({\mathcal{P}}_{2})\hbox{\;$% \rightsquigarrow$\;}{\mathcal{P}}_{2}({\mathcal{P}}_{1})$.
Definition 2.4. The transition functions $g_{\alpha\beta}:U_{\alpha}\cap U_{\beta}\to H(F)$ are defined by the equation $h_{\alpha}k_{\beta}(x,f)=\bigl{(}x,g_{\alpha\beta}(x)(f)\bigr{)},\qquad x\in U% _{\alpha}\cap U_{\beta},\;f\in F.$
Definition 3.1. A category is a topological category if the objects and morphisms form topological spaces such that the source, target and composition maps are continuous.
Definition 2.2. A map $p:E\to B$ is locally homotopy trivial over an open covering $\{U_{\alpha}\}$ if there exist maps $h_{\alpha}$ and $k_{\alpha}$ such that the following diagrams commute: $\displaystyle p^{-1}($ $\displaystyle U_{\alpha})$ $\displaystyle\quad\quad\begin{matrix}h_{\alpha}\\ \longrightarrow\\ \longleftarrow\\ k_{\alpha}\end{matrix}$ $\displaystyle\quad\quad U_{\alpha}\times F$ $\displaystyle\searrow$ $\displaystyle\ \ \swarrow$ $\displaystyle\quad U_{\alpha}$ and $h_{\alpha}$ and $k_{\alpha}$ are mutual fibre homotopy inverses.
Definition 2.1. A map $p:E\to B$ has the WCHP if for every homotopy $H:X\times I\to B$ and $h:X\to E$ such that $ph(x)=H(x,0)$, there exists a homotopy $\tilde{H}:X\times[-1,1]\to E$ such that $\tilde{H}(x,-1)=h(x)$ and $p\tilde{H}(x,t)=H(x,t)$ for $t\in[0,1]$ while $p\tilde{H}(x,t)=H(x,0)$ for $t\in[-1,0].$
Definition 2.5. The collection $\{g_{\sigma}\}$ is called a homotopy transition cocycle for $p:E\to B.$
Definition 3.2. The realization $|\mathcal{C}|$ of a topological category $\mathcal{C}$ is the following space: Let $\mathcal{C}_{0}=\operatorname{Ob}\,\mathcal{C},\ \mathcal{C}_{1}=\operatorname% {Mor}\,\mathcal{C},\ \mathcal{C}_{p}\subset(\operatorname{Mor}\,\mathcal{C})^{p}$ consists of all $p$-tuples $(f_{1},\cdots,f_{p})$ such that $f_{1}\circ\cdots\circ f_{p}$ is defined. Consider the subset $B\mathcal{C}\subset\Delta^{\infty}\times(\mathcal{C}_{1})^{\infty}$ consisting of pairs $(\vec{t},\{g_{ij}\})$ such that 1) $\vec{t}\in\Delta^{\infty}$ 2) $i,j$ runs over all pairs such that $t_{i}t_{j}\neq 0$ 3) $g_{ij}\in\operatorname{Mor}\,\mathcal{C}$ and $g_{ii}=Id_{i}$ and 4) $g_{ij}g_{jk}=g_{ik}$ if $t_{i}t_{j}t_{k}\neq 0$. (Thus Milnor’s reference to “the space of cocyles with values in $\mathcal{C}$.”) Topologize this space by the limit of the quotient topologies of the maps $\Delta^{n}\times\mathcal{C}_{n}\to B\mathcal{C}$ given by $(s_{0},\cdots,s_{n},g_{1},\cdots,g_{n})\to(\vec{t},\{g_{ij}\})$ with $t_{k_{j}}=s_{j}$ for some $k_{0}<k_{1}<\cdots<k_{n}$ and $g_{k_{i}k_{j}}=g_{i+1}\cdots g_{j}$. The universal cover of $B\mathcal{C}$ is given by $U_{i}=\{t_{i}^{-1}(0,1]\}$ and the $g_{ij}$ coordinates regarded as functions $U_{i}\cap U_{j}\to\mathcal{C}$ are universal transition functions. (Strictly speaking, the $U_{i}$ are only point-finite, but following Dold, we can deform the original $t_{i}$ to functions $\bar{t}_{i}$ which are locally finite so the associated $\bar{t}_{i}^{-1}(0,1]$ are also.) Now an open covering $\{U_{\alpha}\}$ can be regarded as a category $\hat{\mathcal{U}}$ in a rather trivial way. For simplicity, well order the index set or, perhaps more naturally, following Segal [9], let the objects be the points of the intersections $U_{\sigma}$ and let the morphisms be given by the inclusions. This is effectively the barycentric subdivision and hence has a natural partial order. Let $\operatorname{Ob}\,\mathcal{C}=\coprod U_{\alpha}$ and $\operatorname{Mor}\,\mathcal{C}=\coprod_{\alpha>\beta}U_{\alpha}\cap U_{\beta}$ with $source(x\in U_{\alpha}\cap U_{\beta})=x\in U_{\alpha}$ and $target(x\in U_{\alpha}\cap U_{\beta})=x\in U_{\beta}.$ Thus the composition is defined only for $x\in U_{\alpha}\cap U_{\beta}\cap U_{\gamma},\alpha>\beta>\gamma$ and $\mathcal{C}_{p}=\coprod U_{\alpha_{0}}\cdots U_{\alpha_{p}}=\coprod U_{\sigma}$ for ordered simplices $\sigma$. We refer to $|\mathcal{U}|$ as the exploded $X$. See Figures 1-3. There is a natural map $\pi:|\mathcal{U}|\to X$ given by forgetting the simplicial cordinates and the multi-index. If the covering is numerable, i.e., admits a subordinate partition of unity $\{p_{\alpha_{0}}(x),\cdots,p_{\alpha_{n}}(x)\}$ for $x\in U_{\sigma},\sigma=(\alpha_{0},\cdots,\alpha_{n})$, there is a corresponding map $\rho:X\to|\mathcal{U}|$. Indeed, this embeds $X$ as a deformation retract of $|\mathcal{U}|$. See Figure 4. Now what is a continuous functor from $\mathcal{U}$ to $\mathcal{C}$? It is a collection of maps $\displaystyle f_{\alpha}:U_{\alpha}$ $\displaystyle\to\operatorname{Ob}\,\mathcal{C}$ $\displaystyle g_{\alpha\beta}:U_{\alpha}\cap U_{\beta}$ $\displaystyle\to\operatorname{Mor}\,\mathcal{C}$ such that $f_{\alpha}=g_{\alpha\beta}f_{\beta}$ and $g_{\alpha\beta}g_{\beta\gamma}=g_{\alpha\gamma}.$ If $\operatorname{Ob}\,\mathcal{C}$ consists of a single point, the first condition is trivial. This is the case for a topological group $G=\mathcal{C}$ and gives rise to the classifying map for a bundle $X\overset{\simeq}{\;\rightarrow}|\mathcal{U}|\to|G|=BG.$ About the same time as Wirth’s dissertation, tom Dieck [14] proved that Milnor’s universal bundle $E_{G}$ classifies numerable $G$-bundles over arbitrary spaces by giving explicit formulas. Later, Wellen [16] in his diplomarbeit extended the classification theorem to the case of groupoids $G$. As we have seen, for a locally trivial fibration, we cannot guarantee the cocycle condition (2) except up to homotopy.
Definition 3.3. Given two topological categories $\mathcal{C}$ and $D$, a functor up to strong homotopy (also known as a homotopy coherent functor) is a collection of maps $\displaystyle F_{0}:\operatorname{Ob}\,\mathcal{C}$ $\displaystyle\to\operatorname{Ob}\,D$ $\displaystyle F_{p}:I^{p-1}\times\mathcal{C}_{p}$ $\displaystyle\to\operatorname{Mor}\,D$ such that $\displaystyle F_{1}(c:$ $\displaystyle x\to y):F_{0}(x)\to F_{0}(y)$ $\displaystyle F_{p}(t_{1},$ $\displaystyle\cdots,t_{p-1},c_{1},\cdots,c_{n})=F_{p-1}(\cdots,\hat{t}_{i},% \cdots,c_{i}c_{i+1},\cdots)$ $\displaystyle\qquad\mbox{if }t_{i}=0$ $\displaystyle=F_{i}(t_{1},\cdots,t_{i-1},c_{1},\cdots,c_{i})F_{p-i}(t_{i+1},% \cdots,c_{i+1},\cdots,c_{p})$ $\displaystyle\qquad\mbox{if }t_{i}=1.$
Definition 4.1. Here we assume $\mathcal{C}$ is an arbitrary small category and let $\mathcal{D}$ be a subcategory. For an arbitrary object $X$ of $\mathcal{C}$ a morphism ${\rm App}_{\mathcal{D}}(X)\xrightarrow{u_{X}}X$ is called the approximation of $X$ within $\mathcal{D}$ if (i) ${\rm App}_{\mathcal{D}}(X)$ is an object in $\mathcal{D}$ and (ii) every morphism $D\xrightarrow{v}X$ with $D\in Ob(\mathcal{D})$ factors uniquely through $u_{X}$, i.e. there exists a unique morphism $D\xrightarrow{v^{\prime}}{\rm App}_{\mathcal{D}}(X)$ such that $v=u_{X}\circ v^{\prime}$. Similarly, the co-approximation ${\rm CoApp}_{\mathcal{D}}(X)$ is the approximation of $X$ within $\mathcal{D}^{op}$ viewed as an object of $\mathcal{C}^{op}$. We do not make any assumptions on the existence of (co)approximations.
Definition 4.11. The (co)cyclic ${\tt B}$-comodule ${\rm App}_{\Lambda}(T_{\bullet}^{\tt B})$ corresponding to a pseudo-para-(co)cyclic ${\tt B}$-comodule $T_{\bullet}$ is called the universal (co)cyclic ${\tt B}$-comodule of $T_{\bullet}$. Moreover, given a functor of the form $\mathcal{F}\colon\mathcal{C}^{\tt B}\xrightarrow{}{\rm{\bf Mod}}({k})$ and a (co)homology functor $\mathcal{H}_{*}$ on the category of (co)cyclic $k$-modules, one can compute $\mathcal{H}_{*}\mathcal{F}({\rm App}_{\Lambda}(T_{\bullet}^{\tt B}))$ We will call this (co)homology as the ${\tt B}$-equivariant $\mathcal{H}$-(co)homology of $T_{\bullet}$ with coefficients in $\mathcal{F}$.
Definition 3.3. Let $C$ and $M$ be two arbitrary objects in $\mathcal{C}$ such that we have a transposition $M\otimes C\xrightarrow{w_{M,C}}C\otimes M$. For every $n\geqslant 0$, we define an $S$-module $P_{n}(C,M)$ in $\mathcal{C}$ as follows: let $P_{n}(C,M)$ is the functor from $S$ to $\mathcal{C}$ given on the objects by $\displaystyle P_{n}(C,M)(0):=$ $\displaystyle C^{\otimes n}\otimes M\otimes C$ $\displaystyle P_{n}(C,M)(1):=$ $\displaystyle C^{\otimes n+1}\otimes M$ Moreover, $P_{n}(C,M)(0\xrightarrow{}1):=\left(C^{\otimes n}\otimes M\otimes C% \xrightarrow{t_{n+2}}C^{\otimes n+1}\otimes M\right)$ is the cyclic permutation coming from the symmetric monoidal structure of $\mathcal{C}$ thus its inverse provides $P_{n}(C,M)(1\xrightarrow{}0)$.
Definition 4.6. A comonad ${\tt B}$ is called left exact (resp. right exact) if ${\tt B}$ commutes with arbitrary small limits (resp. colimits). In other words for any functor $F\colon\mathcal{I}\xrightarrow{}\mathcal{C}$ one has ${\rm lim}_{\mathcal{I}}({\tt B}\circ F)\cong{\tt B}\left({\rm lim}_{\mathcal{I% }}F\right)\text{\ \ \ \ \big{(}resp.\ }{\rm colim}_{\mathcal{I}}({\tt B}\circ F% )\cong{\tt B}\left({\rm colim}_{\mathcal{I}}F\right)\big{)}$ And a comonad is called exact if it is both left and right exact.
Definition 2.1. Fix an object $M$ in $\mathcal{C}$ and a unique morphism $w_{M,X}:M\otimes X\xrightarrow{}X\otimes M$ for each object $X$ chosen from a subset $\mathcal{T}$ of $Ob(\mathcal{C})$. The datum $(M,\mathcal{T},\{w_{M,X}\}_{X\in\mathcal{T}})$ is called a class of transpositions and is denoted by $w$. For such an object $X\in\mathcal{T}$, the morphism $w_{M,X}$ and its inverse $w_{M,X}^{-1}$ if it exists, are going to be denoted by respectively. We do not require transpositions to be invertible, nor do we require the inverses to be transpositions themselves even if they exist.
Definition 3.1. Let $S$ be the category with objects $\{0,1\}$ where there is one unique morphism $i\xrightarrow{}j$ between any two objects $i,j\in\{0,1\}$. A functor $F\colon S\xrightarrow{}\mathcal{C}$ will be called an $S$-module.
Definition 4.3. Recall from [12] that an endo-functor ${\tt B}\colon\mathcal{C}\xrightarrow{}\mathcal{C}$ is called a comonad if there exist natural transformations ${\tt B}\xrightarrow{\Delta}{\tt B}^{2}$ and ${\tt B}\xrightarrow{\varepsilon}id_{\mathcal{C}}$ which fit into commutative diagrams $\xymatrix{{\tt B}^{2}(X)\ar[r]^{{\tt B}(\Delta_{X})}&{\tt B}^{3}(X)&&{\tt B}^{% 2}(X)\ar[r]^{{\tt B}(\varepsilon_{X})}&{\tt B}(X)&\ar[l]_{\varepsilon_{{\tt B}% (X)}}{\tt B}^{2}(X)\\ \ar[u]^{\Delta_{X}}{\tt B}(X)\ar[r]_{\Delta_{X}}&\ar[u]_{\Delta_{{\tt B}(X)}}{% \tt B}^{2}(X)&&&\ar[lu]^{\Delta_{X}}{\tt B}(X)\ar[u]^{id}\ar[ru]_{\Delta_{X}}}$ However, we will diverge from the standard conventions and we will refer an object $X$ as a ${\tt B}$-comodule if there exists a morphism $X\xrightarrow{\rho_{X}}{\tt B}(X)$ such that the following diagrams commute $\xymatrix{{\tt B}(X)\ar[r]^{\Delta_{X}}&{\tt B}^{2}(X)&&{\tt B}(X)\ar[r]^{% \varepsilon_{X}}&X\\ \ar[u]^{\rho_{X}}X\ar[r]_{\rho_{X}}&{\tt B}(X)\ar[u]_{{\tt B}(\rho_{X})}&&&\ar% [lu]^{\rho_{X}}X\ar[u]_{id_{X}}}$ Such objects are called ${\tt B}$-coalgebras in [12] but later we will work with (co)algebras in the category of ${\tt B}$-comodules and it would have been awkward to call them “${\tt B}$-coalgebra coalgebras”. Also, a morphism $X\xrightarrow{f}Y$ between two ${\tt B}$-comodules is called a morphism of ${\tt B}$-comodules if one has a commuting diagram of the form $\xymatrix{\ar[d]_{f}X\ar[r]^{\rho_{X}}&{\tt B}(X)\ar[d]^{{\tt B}(f)}\ar[r]^{% \varepsilon_{X}}&X\ar[d]^{f}\\ Y\ar[r]_{\rho_{Y}}&{\tt B}(Y)\ar[r]_{\varepsilon_{Y}}&Y}$ The full subcategory of ${\tt B}$-comodules in $\mathcal{C}$ is denoted by $\mathcal{C}^{\tt B}$ and the category of ${\tt B}$-comodules and their morphisms is denoted by ${\rm{\bf CoMod}}({{\tt B}})$.
Definition 3.4. Let $\Lambda$ be Connes’ cyclic category [2] and $\Lambda_{\mathbb{N}}$ and $\Lambda_{\mathbb{Z}}$ be the variations of $\Lambda$ as defined in [10]. Let us recall the presentation we will use in this paper: the category $\Lambda_{\mathbb{N}}$ has objects $[n]$ indexed by natural numbers $n\geqslant 0$ and is generated by morphisms $[n]\xrightarrow{\partial^{n}_{j}}[n+1]$, $[n+1]\xrightarrow{\sigma^{n}_{i}}[n]$ and $[n]\xrightarrow{\tau_{n}^{\ell}}[n]$ with $0\leqslant j\leqslant n+1$, $0\leqslant i\leqslant n$ and $\ell\in\mathbb{N}$. These generators are subject to the following relations $\displaystyle\partial^{n+1}_{i}\partial^{n}_{j}=$ $\displaystyle\partial^{n+1}_{j+1}\partial^{n}_{i}\text{ \ \ and \ \ }\sigma^{n% -1}_{j}\sigma^{n}_{i}=\sigma^{n-1}_{i}\sigma^{n}_{j+1}\text{ for }i\leqslant j% \ \ \text{ and }\tau_{n}^{s}\tau_{n}^{t}=\tau_{n}^{s+t}\text{ for }s,t\in% \mathbb{N}$ $\displaystyle\sigma^{n}_{i}\partial^{n}_{i}=$ $\displaystyle\sigma^{n}_{i}\partial^{n}_{i+1}=\tau_{n}^{0}\text{ \ \ and\ \ }% \partial^{n}_{i}\sigma^{n}_{j}=\begin{cases}\sigma^{n+1}_{j+1}\partial^{n+1}_{% i}&\text{ if }i\leqslant j\\ \sigma^{n+1}_{j}\partial^{n+1}_{i+1}&\text{ if }i>j\end{cases}$ $\displaystyle\partial^{n}_{j}\tau_{n}^{i}=$ $\displaystyle\tau_{n+1}^{i+p}\partial^{n}_{q}\text{ where $(i+j)=(n+1)p+q$ % with $0\leqslant q\leqslant n$}$ $\displaystyle\tau_{n}^{i}\sigma^{n}_{j}=$ $\displaystyle\sigma^{n}_{q}\tau_{n+1}^{i+p}\text{ where $(-i+j)=(n+1)(-p)+q$ % with $0\leqslant q\leqslant n$}$ The category $\Lambda_{\mathbb{Z}}$ is an extension of $\Lambda_{\mathbb{N}}$ where we allow morphisms of the form $\tau_{n}^{i}$ with $i\in\mathbb{Z}$. Then $\Lambda$ is a quotient of $\Lambda_{\mathbb{Z}}$ where we put the extra relations $\tau_{n}^{n+1}=id_{n}$ for $n\geqslant 0$. The category $\Lambda_{+}$ is the subcategory of $\Lambda_{\mathbb{N}}$ generated by $\partial^{n}_{j}$ and $\sigma^{n}_{i}$ with only $0\leqslant i\leqslant n$ and $0\leqslant j\leqslant n$. A functor $F\colon\Lambda\longrightarrow\mathcal{C}$ will be referred as a cocyclic module in $\mathcal{C}$ while any functor of the form $F\colon\Lambda_{\mathbb{N}}\longrightarrow\mathcal{C}$ or $F\colon\Lambda_{\mathbb{Z}}\longrightarrow\mathcal{C}$ will be referred as a para-cocyclic module in $\mathcal{C}$. A (para-)cyclic module $F$ in $\mathcal{C}$ is defined to be a (para-)cocyclic module in $\mathcal{C}^{op}$. A morphism between (para-)cocyclic modules $h\colon F\longrightarrow G$ in $\mathcal{C}$ is just a natural transformation of functors.
Definition 2.2. An algebra $(A,\mu_{A},e)$ in $\mathcal{C}$ is called a $w$-transpositive algebra if there exists a morphism $w_{M,X}\colon M\otimes X\xrightarrow{}X\otimes M$ in $w$ such that the following diagram commutes $\xymatrix{\ar[d]_{M\otimes\mu_{A}}M\otimes A\otimes A\ar[r]^{w_{M,A}\otimes A}% &A\otimes M\otimes A\ar[r]^{A\otimes w_{M,A}}&\ar[d]^{\mu_{A}\otimes M}A% \otimes A\otimes M\\ M\otimes A\ar[rr]^{w_{M,A}}&&A\otimes M\\ &\ar[lu]^{M\otimes e}M\ar[ru]_{e\otimes M}}$ One can compare this diagram with the “bow-tie” diagram of entwining structures [1, Diagram 5.5]. However, there one requires $M$ to be a coalgebra and one has similar compatibility conditions on the comultiplication structure. Here we do not require $M$ to be a coalgebra. The interaction between the multiplication morphism and $w_{M,A}$, and its inverse $w_{M,A}^{-1}$ if it exits, will be denoted by Similarly, the interaction between the unit morphism and $w_{M,A}$, and $w_{M,A}^{-1}$ if it exits, will be denoted by $\uput{0.0pt}[0.0](-152.222229pt,0.0pt){M}\uput{0.0pt}[0.0](-95.316727pt,0.0pt)% {M}\uput{0.0pt}[0.0](-45.524399pt,0.0pt){M}\uput{0.0pt}[0.0](-17.07164pt,0.0pt% ){M}{\psline(-149.376968pt,-7.113174pt)(-149.376968pt,-21.339554pt)}{\psline}{% o}(-4.7500,-0.5000)(-4.7500,-0.7500){\psline}{o}(-3.7500,-0.5000)(-3.7500,-0.7% 500){\psline(-92.471451pt,-7.113174pt)(-92.471451pt,-21.339554pt)}{\psline}{o}% (-2.0000,-0.5000)(-2.0000,-0.7500){\psline(-42.679123pt,-7.113174pt)(-42.67912% 3pt,-21.339554pt)}{\psline(-14.226364pt,-7.113174pt)(-14.226364pt,-21.339554pt% )}{\psline}{o}(0.0000,-0.5000)(0.0000,-0.7500){\psline(-149.376968pt,-21.33955% 4pt)(-149.376968pt,-24.896149pt)}{\psline(-135.150589pt,-24.896149pt)(-149.376% 968pt,-32.009338pt)}{\psset{border=2pt}\psline(-149.376968pt,-24.896149pt)(-13% 5.150589pt,-32.009338pt)}{\psline(-135.150589pt,-32.009338pt)(-135.150589pt,-3% 5.565933pt)}{\psline(-135.150589pt,-21.339554pt)(-135.150589pt,-24.896149pt)}{% \psline(-149.376968pt,-32.009