Definition 4.7. Let ${\tt B}$ be a comonad on a category $\mathcal{C}$. A para-(co)cyclic object $T_{\bullet}\colon\Lambda_{\mathbb{N}}\xrightarrow{}\mathcal{C}^{\tt B}$ is called a pseudo-para-(co)cyclic ${\tt B}$-comodule if its restriction to the subcategory $\Lambda_{+}$ factors through ${\rm{\bf CoMod}}({{\tt B}})$.
Definition 3.2. (1) Consider pre-complexes $(C^{\cdot},d_{C}),(D^{\cdot},d_{D})\in P(\mathcal{C})$, graded maps $f,g\in\mathrm{Hom}^{n}(C^{\cdot},D^{\cdot})$ and a homotopy $H:f\longrightarrow g$. Suppose we have lifts $(\overline{C}^{\cdot},\overline{d}_{C}),(\overline{D}^{\cdot},\overline{d}_{D}% )\in P(\overline{\mathcal{C}})$ along $P(F)$ and graded lifts $\overline{f},\overline{g}$. A graded lift of $H$ (along $F$) relative to $\overline{d}_{C},\overline{d}_{D},\overline{f},\overline{g}$ is a graded lift $\overline{H}$ of $H$ which is a homotopy $\overline{H}:\overline{f}\longrightarrow\overline{g}$. We consider the following groupoid $L_{F}(H\,|\,\overline{d}_{C},\overline{d}_{D},\overline{f},\overline{g}):$ 0. Objects are graded lifts of $H$ relative to $\overline{d}_{C},\overline{d}_{D},\overline{f},\overline{g}$. 1. Morphisms from $\overline{H}$ to $\overline{H}^{\prime}$ are graded lifts $\overline{0}:\overline{H}\longrightarrow\overline{H}^{\prime}$ of $0:H\longrightarrow H$ relative to $\overline{d}_{C},\overline{d}_{D},\overline{H},\overline{H}^{\prime}$. (2) Consider cochain complexes $(C^{\cdot},d_{C}),(D^{\cdot},d_{D})\in C(\mathcal{C})$ and a cochain map $f:(C^{\cdot},d_{C})\longrightarrow(D^{\cdot},d_{D})$. For lifts $(\overline{C}^{\cdot},\overline{d}_{C}),(\overline{D}^{\cdot},\overline{d}_{D}% )\in C(\overline{\mathcal{C}})$, we put $L_{F}(f\,|\,\overline{d}_{C},\overline{d}_{D})=L_{F}(f\,|\,\overline{d}_{C},% \overline{d}_{D},0,0),\text{i.e.}$ 0. Objects are lifts of $f$ along $C(F)$ relative to $(\overline{C}^{\cdot},\overline{d}_{C}),(\overline{D}^{\cdot},\overline{d}_{D})$. 1. Morphisms from $\overline{f}$ to $\overline{f}^{\prime}$ are graded lifts of $0:f\longrightarrow f$ relative to $\overline{d}_{C},\overline{d}_{D},\overline{f},\overline{f}^{\prime}$. (3) Consider a cochain complex $(C^{\cdot},d)\in C(\mathcal{C})$ and a graded lift $\overline{C}^{\cdot}$ of $C^{\cdot}$. (a) A graded lift of $d$ along $F$ relative to $\overline{C}^{\cdot}$ is an element of $L_{G(F)}(d:C^{\cdot}\longrightarrow C^{\cdot}[1]\,|\,\overline{C}^{\cdot},% \overline{C}^{\cdot}[1])$. (b) A lift of $d$ along $F$ relative to $\overline{C}^{\cdot}$ is a graded lift $\overline{d}$ of $d$ with $\overline{d}^{2}=0$, i.e. a differential $\overline{d}$ on $\overline{C}^{\cdot}$ making $(\overline{C}^{\cdot},\overline{d})$ into a lift of $(C^{\cdot},d)$ along $C(F)$. We consider the following bigroupoid $L_{F}(d\,|\,\overline{C}^{\cdot}):$ 0. Objects (0-cells) are lifts of $d$ relative to $\overline{C}^{\cdot}$. 1. Morphisms (1-cells) from $\overline{d}$ to $\overline{d}^{\prime}$ are lifts of $1:(C^{\cdot},d)\longrightarrow(C^{\cdot},d)$ relative to $(\overline{C}^{\cdot},\overline{d}),(\overline{C}^{\cdot},\overline{d}^{\prime})$ which are isomorphisms in $C(\overline{\mathcal{C}})$. 2. 2-cells from $\overline{1}$ to $\overline{1}^{\prime}$ are graded lifts of $0:1\longrightarrow 1$ relative to $\overline{d},\overline{d}^{\prime},\overline{1},\overline{1}^{\prime}$.
Definition 6.8. For a complex $C^{\cdot}\in C(\mathcal{C})$, its coflat dimension is defined to be $\mathrm{cd}(C^{\cdot})=\min\{n\in\mathbb{N}\,|\,\forall M\in\mathsf{mod}(R),\,% \forall|i|>n\,\,\mathrm{Ext}^{i}_{R}(M,C^{\cdot})=0\}$ if such an $n$ exists and $\mathrm{cd}(C^{\cdot})=\infty$ otherwise.
Definition 3.1. (1) For an object $C\in\mathcal{C}$, a lift of $C$ along $F$ is an object $\overline{C}\in\overline{\mathcal{C}}$ together with an isomorphism $c:C\cong F(\overline{C})$. A lift $(\overline{C},c)$ of $C$ will often be denoted simply by $\overline{C}$ or $c$. If $F:\overline{\mathcal{C}}\longrightarrow\mathcal{C}$ is right adjoint to a functor $G:\mathcal{C}\longrightarrow\overline{\mathcal{C}}$, a lift of $C$ along $F$ can be represented by a map $G(C)\longrightarrow\overline{C}$. (2) For a map $f:C\longrightarrow C^{\prime}$ in $\mathcal{C}$ and lifts $c:C\cong F(\overline{C})$ and $c^{\prime}:C^{\prime}\cong F(\overline{C^{\prime}})$ along $F$ of $C$ and $C^{\prime}$ respectively, a lift of $f$ (along $F$) relative to $c,c^{\prime}$ is a map $\overline{f}:\overline{C}\longrightarrow\overline{C^{\prime}}$ with $F(\overline{f})c=c^{\prime}f$. The set of all lifts of $f$ along $F$ relative to $c,c^{\prime}$ will be denoted by $L_{F}(f|c,c^{\prime}).$ (3) For $C\in\mathcal{C}$, we consider the following groupoid $L_{F}(C):$ 0. Objects of $L_{F}(C)$ are lifts of $C$ along $F$. 1. Morphisms from $(\overline{C},c:C\cong F(\overline{C}))$ to $(\overline{C}^{\prime},c^{\prime}:C\cong F(\overline{C}^{\prime}))$ are elements of $L_{F}(1_{C}:C\longrightarrow C|c,c^{\prime})$ which are isomorphisms in $\overline{\mathcal{C}}$.
Definition 6.1. We will say that a diagram of functors $\xymatrix{\mathcal{C}\ar[r]^{F}\ar[d]_{H}&\mathcal{C}^{\prime}\ar[d]^{H^{% \prime}}\\ \mathcal{D}\ar[r]_{G}&{\mathcal{D}^{\prime}},}$ satisfies (L) if the following conditions are fulfilled: (1) The diagram is commutative up to natural isomorphism. (2) $F$ and $G$ are fully faithful. (3) If $H^{\prime}(C^{\prime})\cong G(D)$, then there is a $C\in\mathcal{C}$ with $C^{\prime}\cong F(C)$.
